<h3>
    Mass:
</h3>
<p>
    Mass is a central concept to the understanding of dynamics.
    There are three different ways to think of mass.
</p>

<div class = 'definitionBox'>
    <h5>Mass as Matter</h5>
    <p>
        Mass is the amount of matter in an object.
        All of matter is made up of protons, neutrons, and electrons.
        The more protons, neutrons and electrons are contained in a particular object,
        the more mass it has!
        (With protons and neutrons counting about 1000 times as an electron.)
    </p>
</div>

<div class = 'definitionBox'>
    <h5>Inertial Mass:</h5>
    <p>
        The more difficult it is to change the motion of an object
        (to make an object start moving, stop moving, move faster,
        or change direction), the more inertial mass it has.
    </p>
</div>

<div class = 'definitionBox'>
    <h5>Gravitational Mass:</h5>
    <p>
        The ability of mass to attract other mass.
    </p>
</div>

<p>
    All three types of mass are equal to each other!
    More matter means more inertial mass and more
    gravitational mass in precisely the same proportion.
</p>

